Scriptum Magistri Alexandri super libros de Anima, No. 5 33, The description is incomplete, because, between Pecham's book and that of Alexander, is intercalated a long anonymous treatise on the Aristotelian books de animalibus.

Pecharn's commentary begins thus: Incipit scriptum super Etlzicam fratris joliannis de Peliae (de Pecliano is written on the reverse of the fly-leaf). Cum scientie quedam sint de rebus et quedam de signis, cum scientia sit liabitas anime intellective, non erit scientia de signis quibuslibet sed de Signis, que, mediante sensu, comparationem babent essentialiter ad animam intellec- tivam vel ad potentias eius. Hoc autem proprie est sermo sive vox liberalis. It is worthy of note that in commenting on the famous passage in the Ethics concerning ideas, Pecham openly supports the arguments of Plato against Aristotle, appealing to- St. Augustine.
